Kraken2/Bracken data visualization from Nextflow metagenomics training material

User

2025

Reference-based compositional analysis

We used Kraken2/Bracken to perform taxonomic assignment of the raw sequences and estimate species abundance. The procedure included the remotion of reads mapping to the yeast genome. The workflow is proposed by Lu et al.(2022), wrapped by Nextflow.

The analysis of the raw counts was developed using the species abundance data as a Phyloseq object to display absolute and relative abundance, and -Diversity.

Abundance plots

With these plots it is possible to establish differences among samples in terms of the community composition:

Absolute abundance

library(phyloseq)
library(ggplot2)

data_biom <- import_biom(file)
colnames(data_biom@tax_table@.Data)<- c("Kingdom", "Phylum", "Class", "Order", "Family", "Genus", "Species")
plot_bar(data_biom, fill = "Genus")+
    theme_bw()+
    theme(text = element_text(size = 14),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(size=14,hjust=0.5),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1,
                                    size = 12, hjust = 1))+
    labs(y = "Absolute abundance")

Relative abundance

percentages <- transform_sample_counts(data_biom, function(x) x*100 / sum(x) )
df_per <- psmelt(percentages)
df_per$Genus <- as.character(df_per$Genus)
df_per$Genus <- as.factor(df_per$Genus)

ggplot(data=df_per, aes(x=Sample, y=Abundance, fill=Genus))+
    geom_bar(aes(), stat="identity", position="stack", color = "black")+
    theme_bw()+
    theme(text = element_text(size = 14),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(size=14,hjust=0.5),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1,
                                    size = 12, hjust = 1))+
    labs(y = "Relative abundance")

-Diversity

Next, Lets explore the -diversity among samples using two indeces, Chao1 and Shannon:

p = plot_richness(data_biom, measures=c("Chao1", "Shannon"), color = "samples")+
    theme_bw()+
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1,
                                    size = 12, hjust = 1),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 14),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank(),
        strip.text.x = element_text(size = 14),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 10),
        legend.title = element_text(size = 14),
        axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"),
        )+
    labs(x = "Sample",
        color = "Sample")

p + geom_point(size=5, alpha=0.7)

Heatmap

plot_heatmap(data_biom, method = "PCoA", distance = "bray",
            taxa.label = "Genus", taxa.order = "Genus",
            trans=NULL, low="beige", high="red", na.value="beige")+
        theme_bw()+
        theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1,
                                            size = 12, hjust = 1),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 14),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        strip.text.x = element_text(size = 14),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 10),
        legend.title = element_text(size = 14))

Ordination plots

Principal Coordinate Analysis

This dimensionality-reduction technique is useful to review the -diversity, in other words a measure of how alike or different the samples are. To this purpose, we are going to use a Bray-Curtis dissimilarity matrix as a metric of the overall difference among samples:

data.ord <- ordinate(data_biom, "PCoA", "bray")
plot_ordination(data_biom, data.ord, type="split", color="Genus",
                title="biplot")+
    theme_bw()+
    theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 12), axis.title = element_text(size = 14),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 14), strip.text.x = element_text(size = 14),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 14),
        legend.title = element_text(size=14),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"),
        panel.background = element_blank())+
    geom_point(size=5, alpha=0.7)+
    labs(title="Biplot")

Network Analysis

plot_net(data_biom, distance = "bray", type = "taxa",
            maxdist = 0.9, color="Genus")+
        guides(color = guide_legend(ncol = 2))
